data.title: Eat here
data.text: Found the restaurant through Trip Advisor and was a bit reluctant especially regarding food reviews because what I and most people think is good seems to be very different... but in this case we agree.  It located on a side street (just off the main drag) in South San Francisco. Warning: They have no A/C so if you go on a hot day (as we did) be prepared to ask for a lot of ice water. We ordered pork/green onion dumplings, chicken dumplings, spring rolls, cucumber salad and green onion pancakes.  The dumplings are 12 each... we had plenty of takeout!  Lunch was lovely... actually like the dumplings more the next day...the spring rolls are small and crispy, the green onion pancakes were delicious and the cucumber salad was light and very refreshing and it was all very, very affordable.  Others were more adventurous as I looked around the small room and I would've like to have tried some soup but it was just too hot.  Recommended.

data.title: great food and wonderful people
data.text:
i was just looking for a restaurant close to the airport hotel i was in and somehow found this little gem.  as soon as i walked in i knew i had made the right choice; lots of happy diners!  the food was great, as was the service.
when i got back to my room i realized i had left my jacket there.  i called over and they asked where i was.  they drove it over to my hotel for me!  these folks ROCK

data.title: Yummy hole in the wall across the freeway from embassy suites
data.text: Yum.   Walked under the freeway from the Embassy Suites.... About 0.6 miles.   Tiny....    Dumplings, string beans and pancakes were just delicious.    Glad we made the effort to find it!

data.title: This is a hole in the wall restaurant
data.text: Don't expect great decor when you walk into Dumpling Empire.  This is a family owned neighborhood restaurant.  What you get is average dumplings and xiao long bao but the prices were pretty reasonable.  You get what you pay for!

data.title: Well Named Restaurant
data.text:
For those spending the night near San Francisco’s airport, I happily recommend Dumpling Empire. While the décor is stark (think hole-in-the-wall, with about 12 tables and a need for fresh paint), the Northern style of Chinese cooking is excellent. There is a good variety of freshly made, delicious dumplings (12 to an order) served with black vinegar (Beijing style), although a very nice yellow garlic-chili sauce and soy sauce are on each table. 

I had beef-Chinese spinach dumplings and my wife the egg-garlic chive dumplings - both of which were done perfectly. We also had hot and sour soup (Northern, not Sichuan style, in that white pepper rather than Sichuan pepper was used) in a huge bowl, which we couldn’t finish. 

Unusual Chinese greens were also on offer (which I miss from China, rarely seeing them offered in the US) as well as dishes aimed at less adventuresome American taste buds. Service is friendly and attentive and the prices are almost ridiculously low.

Yes, there are other interesting restaurants in South San Francisco, but when I fly through SFO again, I’ll return to Dumpling Empire first.

data.title: xiao long bao and beans
data.text: Cheap eats in a hole-in-the-wall location.  Because I was solo, I didn't order the variety that one would expect when dining with at least one or two other friends.  Had the XLB and some veggies - garlic beans.  All good and hit the spot.  I got their early at about 5:30 and it was already half full.  Quick service.. nothing fancy but just good food!

data.title: Hole In The Wall Dim Sum
data.text: Hidden in a little nook in South San Francisco is this little hole-in-the-wall dim sum cafe where you can get some pretty authentic and delicious dim sum.  Generally they say, eat where the locals eat, well this is one of those places.  Hot, crowded, kind of sketchy but the place is always packed and you can always get a very good meal of little Chinese appetizers called

data.title: Good find for a quick meal
data.text:
This was an easy find restaurant after landing in SFO. Either we were lucky or we were lucky but the place is small and we were able to park right outside and get a table quickly ! The line started forming after we came in. The 6 pcs of Xiao long pao was juicy and the beef brisket soup was delicious on a cold night. Word of advice- if you're trying this soup out first time, tell them to skip the fungus and not put it in your soup ( pic enclosed).
Other dishes were the other pork dumplings (12 pcs) that looked yummy. We ordered the beef ho fan noodles and were disappointed bec the beef was overcooked and tough to eat !
Not too expensive of a place and might give it another try when I'm in the area.

data.title: Stumbled onto this small, family run restaurant.
data.text: Homemade noodles and dumplings. Large portions. Tasty hot and sour soup, maybe the best I ever tasted!. Unpretentious, excellent fresh food!

data.title: Good Assortment, Nice Suprise
data.text: These are not the best dumplings I've had but they are perfectly fine and there are lots of choices that are not dumplings. Had pork and shrimp with chives which were delicious and chicken with corn which were just OK. Pan Fried Soup dumplings were tasty but sans soup. Dough on the dumplings was a bit thick and chewy, but I happen to like it that way. Pan-fried radish cakes were exceptional. Other stuff, especially wood ears with garlic and the tendon soup looked very good. If you're staying near the airport, give it a try. Portions are big, prices are low, and you won't find this in Peoria

data.title: Great Spot!
data.text: Hit the jackpot. I love dumplings and this place had them all. I had the pork dumplings with chives and the dim sum pan fried soup dumplings. Both were delicious and washed it down with at tsing Tao beer. Authentic and delicious, place was packed but turned over quickly.

data.title: Go for the food, not ambiance
data.text: Went here with my husband and adult daughter. I was skeptical when I went into a very plain, spartan and cramped restaurant. But, the food was worth the visit. The price was reasonable, portions generous and the dumplings delicious. The green beans with garlic were great. Our favorite was the marinated beef in sesame pancakes.

data.title: It's okay
data.text: I went to this restaurant for takeout.  I had to wait quite a while, and the food I got was okay, not amazing.  Really a hole-in-the-wall.

data.title: Best Real Chinese
data.text:
Although many places in the States have Chinese restaurants, San Francisco has much more to choose from-- but many of these are like in the rest of the country.. Looking for preparations more like we experienced in Shanghai, Xian, Guilin, etc, we found Chinese Empire to meet our taste expectations. We loved the garlic green beans, the selection of dumplings and dim sum was amazing--pork, shrimp, vegetarian all had subtle but excellent flavors. The Shanghai soup dumplings were good, but we were not big fans in China but these were excellent.
I don't care whether a place has fancy decorations--I'll eat Italian from a gas station or BBQ from the roadside cooker, as long it's tasty.

data.title: Dumplings, dumplings........
data.text: The restaurant is very small and has seating for about 40 persons. Dumplings are some of the best I have had outside of China especially Xian, Chengdu and Shanghai.  Try to get there early in the workday prior to 11:30 and after 2:00 p.m..  Bio tech firms are drawn to the place like bees to flowers.  Weekends have the same rule.

data.title: No Frills, Good Food
data.text:
Definitely a Hole in the Wall restaurant. Nothing fancy about the place. 10-12 tables. Not much decor. What they do is serve simple Chinese finger food and they do it well. Went on a lazy Sunday afternoon about 4:30PM. Maybe eight customers. When we left, most of the tables were taken. Very delicious food. Had the owner give us suggestions on what to order. We were not disappointed. Had the Hot and Sour Soup, Pork and Cabbage Dumplings, Garlic Green Beans and the Chive Pancake.
Plenty to take home, which we did. Satisfied Completely.  No frills, just good food.

data.title: Not Bad
data.text:
FOOD:  
The dishes that we tried at this hole-in-the-wall were fairly decent.  The lamb dumplings were quite tasty.  The spicy beef noodle was good but would be better with more meat to balance out the noodle.  The beef tendon slices were very appetizing and highly satisfactory.  The spicy chicken pot was just so-so (the flavors were a bit too subtle for my taste).

SERVICE:  
The service here was really nice.  Our waitress was very courteous and friendly.

PRICE:  
We thought the price was a bit high.  Our bill averaged out to around $18.50 per person.

data.title: Small location good flavors
data.text: Go here for lunch. This is very small dive. Eat the dumplings and green beans with garlic.  That is what everyone else was having. Not the cleanest restaurant but I did like the food. 18 dollars with tip.  It is well reviewed on yelp.
